pq:text.pq:tspan: WOW! Your program is really progressing!
I have a great idea for turning this into a small game.
First we need to learn to work with mouse.
Is that hard?
No harder anything you have already done
You can read the mouse X, Y location as a Point2D.
Yeah!
Each Point2D represents a location, an X and a Y value.
you can read these using mousePoint variable and mousePoint.X and mousePoint.Y.
What can we do with this point value?
I think we should use it to position a crosshair image on the screen.
Sounds cool, let's give it to go.
Can we get it to do something when we click on a bug?
Yeah, we could play a squash sound.
Great idea! What do you think you need to do in order to achieve this?
I think we worked it out! The X value of the point must be between the X value of the sprite, and sprite's X value plus its width ->Sprite.X<=MousePoint.X <=sprite.X + sprite.Width
That's it!
SwinGame can do this for you with Physics.IsSpriteOnScreenAt(sprite, Xpos, Ypos).
WOW! That makes it so easy.
But it's great to understand it!
Now I also want to play on animation when the user hits a bug.
SwinGame has support for animated sprites
There sprites use a sheet of images.
Each sheet has a number of images, called cells.
Yeah, each cell has the same width and a height.
The sprite animates by showing each cell a number of times before moving to the next cell.
how do you achieve this in a program?
There is a version of CreateSprite that is used to create an animated sprite.
It takes the image sheet, and details about the number of times to show an image => each image's width and height and the number of cells on the sheet.
Do you need to manage which cell to draw?
No, it's all taken care of for you by UpdateSprite.
Ok, so when the user clicks a bug we can create a new sprite and have it drawn.
Let's give it to go!
